[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "For.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—This particle would naturally not be expressed in English. It was a reason for the question which had been asked just before: “For the Law ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "does",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " supply a case in point.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The one by a bondmaid.—Hagar, it seems from Genesis 16:1, was an Egyptian. The word for “bondmaid” was not confined to this sense in earlier Greek, but was used for any young girl.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The one by a bondmaid.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Hagar, it seems from ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 16:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", was an Egyptian. The word for “bondmaid” was not confined to this sense in earlier Greek, but was used for any young girl.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4:21-27 The difference between believers who rested in Christ only, and those who trusted in the law, is explained by the histories of Isaac and Ishmael. These things are an allegory, wherein, beside the literal and historical sense of the words, the Spirit of God points out something further. Hagar and Sarah were apt emblems of the two different dispensations of the covenant. The heavenly Jerusalem, the true church from above, represented by Sarah, is in a state of freedom, and is the mother of all believers, who are born of the Holy Spirit. They were by regeneration and true faith, made a part of the true seed of Abraham, according to the promise made to him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For it is written - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Abraham had two sons - Ishmael and Isaac. Abraham subsequently had several sons by Keturah after the death of Sarah; Genesis 26:1-6. But the two sons by Hagar and Sarah were the most prominent, and the events of their lives furnished the particular illustration which Paul desired.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Abraham had two sons - Ishmael and Isaac. Abraham subsequently had several sons by Keturah after the death of Sarah; ",
            "children": []
