  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For it is written",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "γέγραπται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "γάρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "for the Scripture saith.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The phrase does not here, as it does usually, introduce the citation of a text, but prefaces a brief summary of facts; these facts being recited in words gathered out of the Septuagint Version of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". and 21, in much the same way as the story of Melchisedec is sketched in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 7:1-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "That",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Abraham had two sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὅτι Ἀβραὰμ δύο υἱοὺς ἔσχεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that Abraham had gotten two sons",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἔσχεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not exactly equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "εϊχεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Attention has been drawn to other sons born of Keturah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 25:1, 2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), who both in ancient and in modern days (see Windisch-mann) have been very plausibly interpreted as analogously pointing forward allegorically to those heretical bodies, now vanished, which threatened such danger to the Church in the first centuries. But the apostle's concern here is exclusively with the posture of affairs subsisting at the time of Hagar's and Ishmael's expulsion from the patriarch's family, quoted in ver. 30 from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Even if he had seen fit by allegorical exposition to apply Scripture to those dire forms of utterly perverted Christianity, which he certainly did look forward to as about to arise, it is very questionable whether he would have conceded to them so venerable a parentage as having Abraham for their forefather. Mosaism in its place was a thing of Divine origin, even as Christianity itself was, both of them \"covenants\" of God; not so the monstrous forms of Gnostic and Manichean teaching which horrified the primitive Church. In fact, typology, that is to say, the interpretation of Old Testament Scripture as bearing a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "designed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " allegorical sense, requires very cautious handling. The tracing of analogies is an interesting and pleasing exercise of theological ingenuity; but it is one thing to trace a parallelism, and a quite different thing to detect a latent predictive sense intended by the Holy Spirit. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The one by a bondmaid",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek_word",
        "text": "e%na e)k th  =   paidi/skh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "one by the handmaid",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the expression pointing to the individual mother known from the sacred history. The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "παιδίσκη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in classical Greek means a girl either slave or free. In the Septuagint it is generally a slave (not, however, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ruth 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it renders the Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "na'arah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); in the New Testament it is always a maidservant. St. Paul borrows the word from the Septuagint of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". and 21, where it renders the Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "shiphehah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Hagar was the personal property of Sarah. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The other by a freewoman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καὶ ἕνα ἐκ τῆς ἐλευθέρας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and one by the freewoman.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The word \"freewoman\" is never applied to Sarah in the story in Genesis; not even in the passage freely quoted in ver. 30; but it was an obviously true description, and with perfect fairness introduced in antithesis to Hagar. As applied to one holding so princessly a position in the story as Sarah, the idea of a freewoman stands coloured with a deep tincture of dignity. Galatians 4:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For (γάρ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Your determination to be under the law is opposed by Scripture, if you will understand it, for it is written, etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A bondmaid (τῆς παιδίσκης)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The bondmaid, indicating a well known character, Hagar, Genesis 16:3. The word in Class. means also a free maiden; but in N.T. always a slave. So almost always in lxx; but see Ruth 4:12; Judith 12:13. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The bondmaid, indicating a well known character, Hagar, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 16:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The word in Class. means also a free maiden; but in N.T. always a slave. So almost always in lxx; but see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ruth 4:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; Judith 12:13. ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
